postcontent:
Ladies and gentlemen up for sale is my original Israeli military industries galil arm converted to semi auto with all compliance parts.  I have spent the last year and a half building this light machine gun for my “end of days gun” and I despise the idea of parting with it but something has come up that I can not ignore so I must part with it.  For those of you who don’t know the galil arm is a .223 caliber light machine gun model of the galil family, and is fitted with an integrated bi pod/barbwire cutter and a longer barrel than any other model. It is also fitted with a ventilated wood handgaurd to keep it cool during sustained fire.  The arm model was normally used with the 50 round magazines of winch I have 3 it will come with a standerd 35 round magazine,  but the interesting thing is that there is an adapter to make it accept any M16 or AR15 type magazine winch is one of the many reasons I chose this particular gun to defend myself and everything I care about.  Weather its the rock solid AK action or the flip up tritium night sights or even the built in bottle opener (yea it relay has one) the galil arm is the gun that I wanted by my side but I have more pressing matters.  The gun itself is nearly complete only a few minor finishing details, the biggest of winch is that the receiver still needs to be Parkerizing.  Other than that its minor thing that only the most detail oriented of us need worry about.  If you are willing to wait I will Parkerizing the receiver for you but I must receive payment as soon as possible but I only need half now and the other half later.

Ohio rapid fire receiver

hand made magazine floor plate

title: For Sale/Trade:  Customized Mosin Nagant M91/30... not your usual 7.62x54r
postcontent:
If you've made it this far you're at least halfway interested in a Mosin Nagant. Let me help you. 

You're probably asking yourself "Why do I want a Nagant? Why wouldn't I just buy myself a .308?" Well let me answer that for you... ammo prices. Yep shop around on the ammo. You can shoot this gun for right about what it cost to shoot your grandpa's 22. Sure that's a slight exaggeration but seriously, you can shoot these things all day long for little of nothing. Plus you probably like the nostalgia of a gun that helped decide WW2.

Why this one? Well look at it. The standard Mosin Nagants are UGLY... this one isn't. Plus it's a 1942, which is a fine vintage. And it's one of the better built Tula guns. And there's the chance it might have the faint sniper markings over the star, which means it would be one of the more accurate M91/30s. And the bore is great. And it already has a scope, bayonet, ammo pouches, and just enough ammo with it to put a smile on your face. Oh and all the numbers match.

Also comes with the original wooden stock which I didn't take a pic of because they're hideous. Feel free to email me questions, concerns, recipes, pics of your beautiful wife, or information on the gun you want to trade me.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Winchester Model 94 30-30 lever action rile
postcontent:
ultimate lever-action design.    Reasonable shape.  It can be near perfect with a little effort.  Serial number about 4,000,000 = 1975.    No box, no papers... a great hunting rifle.  You can restore this and create significant price appreciation.  

Winchester Model 1894 (also known as Winchester .30-30 rifle, Winchester 94, Win 94,, .30-30 Winchester, or simply .30-30) is a lever-action rifle which became one of the most famous and popular hunting rifles. It was designed by John Browning in 1894 to chamber .30 caliber rounds loaded with smokeless powder, and was produced by Winchester Repeating Arms Company through 1980 and then by U.S. Repeating Arms under the Winchester brand until they ceased to manufacture rifles in 2006. The rifles are back in production today, being made by the Miroku company of Japan and imported into the United States by the Browning Arms company of Morgan, Utah.

The Model 1894 has been referred to as the "ultimate lever-action design" by firearms historians such as RL Wilson and Hal Herring. The Model 1894 is the rifle credited with the name "Winchester" being used to refer to all rifles of this type and was the first commercial sporting rifle to sell over 7,000,000 units.[1]

1. Cut at shoulder
2. Full length sized and deprimed
3. Trimmed with Lee case length gauge (1.359/1.360)
4. Case mouth chamfered inside and out
5. Ran through sizing die again.
6. Crimps removed
7. Primer pockets cleaned
8. Tumbled
9. Polished

title: For Sale/Trade:  J Stevens Visible Loading .22 & W. Richards Double 12 gauge
location: Nw Suburbs, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Let me start by saying I have not fired either guns. And you should have a qualified gunsmith examine if you are going to fire. 

After saying that I believe the .22 J Stevens to be a "gallery gun" from 1910 to 1920. And being a gallery gun it was never meant for hi-power/velocity modern rounds. I believe it to take CB rounds. CB's are a bullet in the case and no powder, just the primer. So I repeat you cannot shoot modern ammo through this gun. Ok as for the gun itself. Action works, trigger works has the sights and it looks like everything is original. The furniture: The forearm/slide is really nice for its age. The wrist has a chunk missing and is wired and taped up. The rest of the stock is ok. It has dents a crack and a few gouges. 

The 12 Gauge: I think it's a twelve. Has everything, except a screw to hold on one of the hammers. Side by side barrels actually look silver. But only because, in my opinion looks like someone took some steel wool to them. Maybe going to blue it? Double triggers work, exposed hammers work, pins are there and work but are a bit sticky. Made by W. Richards. Not to be confused with Westley Richards. I think about 1890??? Must be black Powder and not meant for modern high pressure ammo. 

I personally will not shoot these guns and consider them wallhangers.

Looking for an offer of cash for one or the other or both. Also willing to trade.

title: For Sale:  AR FIVE-SEVEN ON T15-BDX* 5.7X28MM*3X 50 RND MAGS
postcontent: Up for auction is a fantastic AR-15 style rifle with an AR Five-Seven Upper installed. The rifle fires the potent 5.7X28mm round, which depending on bullet choice, is a perfect varmint round but can also penetrate Level IIIA body armor. The magazine capacity is 50 rounds and this auction comes with a total of three original manufacturer (AR-Five-Seven) Magazines. That is 150 rounds in three magazines! This is previously owned, but has fired only a couple of boxes of ammo. The AR Five-Seven upper has picatinny rails on the top, bottom, and sides. These are currently equipped with mostly Knights Armaments Inserts. The Lower receiver is a Tactical Innovations T15-BDX milled receiver with integral trigger-guard. This is one of the best and strongest receivers available, and is marked “multi-caliber” so that you are not constrained to any particular caliber. If you want 22 LONG RIFLE, 9mm LUGER, 5.56 NATO/.223 REM, 50 Beowulf or any caliber upper in-between which can fit a standard AR/15 receiver, you can fit it to the T15-BDX. The trigger is an upgrade over the standard AR trigger. It also has an ERGO grip pistol-grip and a BUSHMASTER collapsible butt-stock. Although it has all this versatility, you probably will want to leave it just like it is, because this is a great performer, and the higher magazine capacity definitely outweighs the slightly greater power of the 5.56 NATO round. Also, because the magazine is on the top, you can slightly modify a standard AR-15 magazine (without follower or spring) to act as a brass catcher, since the expended casings fall down through the magazine well. There are a number of situations where leaving spent casings scattered around is a distinct disadvantage. Other than statements made herein, there are no representations except that you will get the firearm in the pictures if you make the winning bid and comply with the requirements of the auction.
